145":"1145","1166":"1166","living 12 November 1234":"1234","about 1152":"circa 1152","1109":"1109","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Legsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Legsby, Lincolnshire, England","Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Durham, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Thwing, Yorkshire, England":"Thwing, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1145–living 1246":"about 1145–1246","1145–1246":"1145–1246","1156–Female":"1156–Deceased","1178–1234":"1178–1234","1166–Male":"1166–Deceased","1109–1152":"1109–1152","1152":"1152","living 1246":"1246","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","Abt 1145":"about 1145","1234":"1234","1178":"1178","1156":"1156","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","living 12 November 1234":"1234","about 1152":"about 1152","1109":"1109","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Legsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Legsby, Lincolnshire, England","Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Durham, England, United Kingdom","Thwing, Yorkshire, England":"Thwing, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"or","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Jewish (Israeli): from Hebrew <i>or</i> ‘light’, a Hebraicized form of various original Ashkenazic surnames.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 柯, see   Ke   1.","Chinese: Hokkien form of the surname 胡, see   Hu   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Ke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Heng, Yong, Bin, Song, Yan, Zhi, Cheng, Chih-Ming, Chun-Yen, Fan, Fong, Gang.  Vietnamese Lan, Hai, Hoa, Le Van, Mui, Tuy.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 柯, meaning ‘bough, stalk’ in Chinese: (i) from the first element of the personal name Ke Lu (柯盧), personal name of a prince of the state of Wu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the first element of the placename Ke Ze (柯澤), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to an official in the state of Qi during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) traced back to the Qiang ethnic group in ancient western China and the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iv) adopted as a surname by the Ke Ba (柯拔) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: variant of   Ge  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Thweng","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place so called in East Yorkshire, named with Old Norse <i>thvengr</i> or Old English <i>thweng</i> ‘narrow strip of land’.","History: Martha Thwing (died 1774) is buried in the King's Chapel Burying Ground in Boston MA."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":70,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":79,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert FitzRobert or de Thweng was born about 1145, in Thwing, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Robert De Thweng. He had at least 1 son with Emma de Lund. He died in 1246, in Thwing, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 102."},"et":{"Abt 1145–living 1246":"umbes 1145–1246","1145–1246":"1145–1246","1156–Female":"1156–Surnud","1178–1234":"1178–1234","1166–Male":"1166–Surnud","1109–1152":"1109–1152","1152":"1152","living 1246":"1246","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","Abt 1145":"umbes 1145","1234":"1234","1178":"1178","1156":"1156","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","living 12 November 1234":"1234","about 1152":"umbes 1152","1109":"1109","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Legsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Legsby, Lincolnshire, England","Durham, England, Un